TY  - JOUR
T1  - Income Distribution and the Aggregate Consumption Function
AU  - Musgrove, Philip
Y1  - 1980/06/01
PY  - 1980
DA  - 1980/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260883
DO  - 10.1086/260883
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 504
EP  - 525
VL  - 88
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Household consumption propensities are related to income above subsistence levels. Aggregation over households makes the total propensity depend on income level, concentration, and asymmetry; distributional effects interact with income per capita. Estimates using both nominal and real incomes and distributional data from 101 surveys in over 30 countries show no significant effect of inequality on consumption. Reasonable estimates are obtained for subsistence income ($300 real) and the asymptotic consumption propensity (0.70-0.75) using only income level. Either distributional effects are weak or the available data are inappropriate; a correct specification would require data on income per head within households.
AB  - Household consumption propensities are related to income above subsistence levels. Aggregation over households makes the total propensity depend on income level, concentration, and asymmetry; distributional effects interact with income per capita. Estimates using both nominal and real incomes and distributional data from 101 surveys in over 30 countries show no significant effect of inequality on consumption. Reasonable estimates are obtained for subsistence income ($300 real) and the asymptotic consumption propensity (0.70-0.75) using only income level. Either distributional effects are weak or the available data are inappropriate; a correct specification would require data on income per head within households.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260883
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260883
Y2  - 2024/03/22
